{"title_page": "Jebamalai Vinanchiarachi", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=August 2016}}\n{{BLP sources|date=July 2016}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name             = Jebamalai Vinanchiarachi\n| image            = Dr Jebamalai Vinanchiarachi.jpg\n| caption          = \n| birth_date       = \n| birth_place      = \n| alma_mater       = [[University of Madras]]\n| residence        = \n| occupation       = Economist, former [[United Nations]] official, writer, analyst\n}}\n\n'''Jebamalai Vinanchiarachi''' (commonly known as Arachi) is an India-born economist.\n\n== Education ==\nVinanchiarachi completed his PhD from the [[University of Madras]], Tamil Nadu.<ref name=\"JayneMinde2002\">{{cite book\n  | author1   = Thomas S. Jayne\n  | author2   = Isaac J. Minde\n  | author3   = Gem Argwings-Kodhek\n  | title     = Perspectives on Agricultural Transformation: A View from Africa\n  | url       = https://books.google.com/books?id=u9NUdCeW-3MC&pg=PA266\n  | year      = 2002\n  | publisher = Nova Publishers\n  | isbn      = 978-1-59033-344-0\n  | pages     = 266\u2013\n  | quote     = VINANCHIARACHI JEBAMALAI studied economics at the University of Madras, India. His degrees include an M.A., M.Phil., D.H.Ed., and Ph.D., with distinctions. Currently he is working for the Industrial Policies and Research Branch of the ...\n}}</ref> He is an alumnus of several academic institutions in South India.\n\n* 1986\u20131989: Ph.D. Economics, University of Madras, Chennai, India\n* 1978\u20131979: MPhil. Economics, University of Madras, Chennai, India\n* 1977\u20131978: D.H.Ed.Education, University of Madras, Chennai, India\n* 1968\u20131970: M.A. Economics, St. Joseph's College, Trichy, India\n* 1964\u20131967: B.A. Economics, St. Xavier's College, Tirunelveli, India\n\n== Career ==\nVinanchiarachi worked as Senior Economist with the [[United Nations Industrial Development Organization]] (UNIDO) from 1987 to 2009.<ref name=\"Organization2009\">{{cite book\n  | author    = United Nations Industrial Development Organization\n  | title     = Industrial Development Report 2009: Breaking in and Moving Up \u2013 New Industrial Challenges for the Bottom Billion and the Middle-Income Countries\n  | url       = https://books.google.com/books?id=eVsDrogCVm0C&pg=PR9\n  | date      = 1 March 2009\n  | publisher = United Nations Publications\n  | pages     = 9\u2013\n  | quote     = The in-house UNIDO team was led by Jebamalai Vinanchiarachi, Principal Adviser to the Director-General of UNIDO ...\n}}</ref>\nHe was the UNIDO Country Representative to [[Sudan]], Djiubouti and Yemen from 2003\u20132006. His years in Sudan were marked by contribution to industrial development in North Africa and increased South-South economic cooperation.{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n\nHe served as the Principal Advisor to the Director General of UNIDO based in Vienna, Austria from 2006 to 2009. Vinanchiarachi is a speaker on development issues and has given numerous speeches at the United Nations and academic institutions. He has received numerous awards at an international level.{{Citation needed|date=July 2016}} In January 2012, he received recognition as the 'Outstanding [[Non-resident Indian and person of Indian origin|Non-Resident Indian]] contribution on an International level' from the Global Indian Association in Dubai, UAE. He is also the recipient of the dynamic Indian of the Millennium given by the KG Foundation. In October 2018 the Auckland-based Indian Newslink gave him a commemorative award for his distinguished contribution to the international community. \n\nBetween 2010\u20132012, Vinanchiarachi was a Visiting Fellow at the [[University of Malaya]] in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia.<ref name=\"RasiahKanagasundram2013\">{{cite book\n  | author1   = Rajah Rasiah\n  | author2   = Thiruchelvam Kanagasundram\n  | author3   = Keun Lee\n  | title     = Innovation and Learning Experiences in Rapidly Developing East Asia\n  | url       = https://books.google.com/books?id=zYXaAAAAQBAJ&pg=PT7\n  | date      = 13 September 2013\n  | publisher = Taylor & Francis\n  | isbn      = 978-1-317-98311-8\n  | pages     = 7\u2013\n  | quote     = Jebamalai Vinanchiarachi, former Principal Adviser to the Director General of UNIDO, is currently avisiting Senior Research Fellow at the University of Malaya, Kuala Lumpur.\n}}</ref>\nHe was appointed as Director, Cleemis School of Management Studies, Thiruvananthapuram between 2013\u201314. Since 2016 he has been acting as the Chairman of the Experience Foundation, South India. He continues to engage in international consultancy work for the United Nations and partner organisations and lectures at academic institutions internationally on business futurology, the new industrial era, patterns of development, and innovation systems.  \nJebamalai Vinanchiarachi won several distinctions and awards. He won the coveted Raja Sir Annamalai Chettiar Gold Medal from St. Joseph\u2019s College, Trichy, India, for being the best outgoing student of M.A. Economics in 1969. He was awarded twice UNIDO Director General\u2019s award for outstanding performance and professional excellence.\u00a0 The Vienna-based Kerala Community gave him a life-time achievement award as a great scholar and gentle helper. A similar life-time achievement award was given to him by the management of Pioneer Kumarasamy College, Nagercoil, where he started his career as a lecturer in 1970, for professional excellence. At the first World Tamil Economic Conference, he was honoured with the coveted award \u201cTamil Crown Jewel of the World\u201d.  He is also the recipient of the 2013 Global Indian Association Award for International Excellence. The KG foundation recently conferred the \u201cDynamic Indian of the Millennium Award\u201d upon him. In October 2018, the Indian Newslink, Auckland, New Zealand, honoured him with a special commemorative  award for his distinguished services to international communities and the Indian Diaspora. \n\nBy a dint  hard work and dedication he won the approbation of many world-wide for  his innovative and practical ideas for fostering sustainable development, with an accent sectoral innovation systems and  social inclusion.   Areas of specialization include new sources of dynamic growth, sustainable sources of livelihoods, and determinants of competitiveness, national industrial innovation systems, private sector development and institutional capacity building for strengthening national and sectoral innovation systems. \nAfter retiring from UNIDO,  he worked briefly for the Asian Development Bank (ADB), as an expert  on cluster networking.  Currently working on the rapidly changing facets of the new industrial revolution, in co-authorship with a few experts, which will soon be published as a book by UNIDO. Recently coined the syllabus for a new subject called \u201cBusiness Futurology\u201d for the students of management.  He briefly served as   an expert for EGMs organized by  the knowledge management unit of the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), Vienna, Austria,  and made scholarly inputs to non-nuclear energy innovation systems. He also worked as a lead consultant for  the UN FAO, Rome, Italy, on an operational strategy paper for fostering agribusiness in Syria and Oman.\n\n== Writings ==\nVinanchiarachi has authored and co-authored more than a hundred articles{{citation needed|date=June 2016}} and reports on industrial growth, South-South cooperation, trade liberalization in South-east Asia and sustainable growth models for newly industrializing countries. Most notable books include:\n\n* ''India's Time''\n* ''Myths and Realities of East Asian Model of Development''\n* ''Demand Analysis''\n* ''Rethinking Development Realities''\n* ''Intervene to Industrialize'' (co-author)\n*   The Poverty of Economic Thinking\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}4. https://in.linkedin.com/in/jebamalaivinanchiarachi\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vinanchiarachi, Jebamalai}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=August 2016}}\n{{BLP sources|date=July 2016}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name             = Jebamalai Vinanchiarachi\n| image            = Dr Jebamalai Vinanchiarachi.jpg\n| caption          = \n| birth_date       = \n| birth_place      = \n| alma_mater       = [[University of Madras]]\n| residence        = \n| occupation       = Economist, former [[United Nations]] official, writer, analyst\n}}\n\n'''Jebamalai Vinanchiarachi''' (commonly known as Arachi) is an India-born economist.\n\n== Education ==\nVinanchiarachi completed his PhD from the [[University of Madras]], Tamil Nadu.<ref name=\"JayneMinde2002\">{{cite book\n  | author1   = Thomas S. Jayne\n  | author2   = Isaac J. Minde\n  | author3   = Gem Argwings-Kodhek\n  | title     = Perspectives on Agricultural Transformation: A View from Africa\n  | url       = https://books.google.com/books?id=u9NUdCeW-3MC&pg=PA266\n  | year      = 2002\n  | publisher = Nova Publishers\n  | isbn      = 978-1-59033-344-0\n  | pages     = 266\u2013\n  | quote     = VINANCHIARACHI JEBAMALAI studied economics at the University of Madras, India. His degrees include an M.A., M.Phil., D.H.Ed., and Ph.D., with distinctions. Currently he is working for the Industrial Policies and Research Branch of the ...\n}}</ref> He is an alumnus of several academic institutions in South India.\n\n* 1986\u20131989: Ph.D. Economics, University of Madras, Chennai, India\n* 1978\u20131979: MPhil. Economics, University of Madras, Chennai, India\n* 1977\u20131978: D.H.Ed.Education, University of Madras, Chennai, India\n* 1968\u20131970: M.A. Economics, St. Joseph's College, Trichy, India\n* 1964\u20131967: B.A. Economics, St. Xavier's College, Tirunelveli, India\n\n== Career ==\nVinanchiarachi worked as Senior Economist with the [[United Nations Industrial Development Organization]] (UNIDO) from 1987 to 2009.<ref name=\"Organization2009\">{{cite book\n  | author    = United Nations Industrial Development Organization\n  | title     = Industrial Development Report 2009: Breaking in and Moving Up \u2013 New Industrial Challenges for the Bottom Billion and the Middle-Income Countries\n  | url       = https://books.google.com/books?id=eVsDrogCVm0C&pg=PR9\n  | date      = 1 March 2009\n  | publisher = United Nations Publications\n  | pages     = 9\u2013\n  | quote     = The in-house UNIDO team was led by Jebamalai Vinanchiarachi, Principal Adviser to the Director-General of UNIDO ...\n}}</ref>\nHe was the UNIDO Country Representative to [[Sudan]], Djiubouti and Yemen from 2003\u20132006. His years in Sudan were marked by contribution to industrial development in North Africa and increased South-South economic cooperation.{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n\nHe served as the Principal Advisor to the Director General of UNIDO based in Vienna, Austria from 2006 to 2009. Vinanchiarachi is a speaker on development issues and has given numerous speeches at the United Nations and academic institutions. He has received numerous awards at an international level.{{Citation needed|date=July 2016}} In January 2012, he received recognition as the 'Outstanding [[Non-resident Indian and person of Indian origin|Non-Resident Indian]] contribution on an International level' from the Global Indian Association in Dubai, UAE. He is also the recipient of the dynamic Indian of the Millennium given by the KG Foundation. In October 2018 the Auckland-based Indian Newslink gave him a commemorative award for his distinguished contribution to the international community. \n\nBetween 2010\u20132012, Vinanchiarachi was a Visiting Fellow at the [[University of Malaya]] in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia.<ref name=\"RasiahKanagasundram2013\">{{cite book\n  | author1   = Rajah Rasiah\n  | author2   = Thiruchelvam Kanagasundram\n  | author3   = Keun Lee\n  | title     = Innovation and Learning Experiences in Rapidly Developing East Asia\n  | url       = https://books.google.com/books?id=zYXaAAAAQBAJ&pg=PT7\n  | date      = 13 September 2013\n  | publisher = Taylor & Francis\n  | isbn      = 978-1-317-98311-8\n  | pages     = 7\u2013\n  | quote     = Jebamalai Vinanchiarachi, former Principal Adviser to the Director General of UNIDO, is currently avisiting Senior Research Fellow at the University of Malaya, Kuala Lumpur.\n}}</ref>\nHe was appointed as Director, Cleemis School of Management Studies, Thiruvananthapuram between 2013\u201314. Since 2016 he has been acting as the Chairman of the Experience Foundation, South India. He continues to engage in international consultancy work for the United Nations and partner organisations and lectures at academic institutions internationally on business futurology, the new industrial era, patterns of development, and innovation systems.  \nJebamalai Vinanchiarachi won several distinctions and awards. He won the coveted Raja Sir Annamalai Chettiar Gold Medal from St. Joseph\u2019s College, Trichy, India, for being the best outgoing student of M.A. Economics in 1969. He was awarded twice UNIDO Director General\u2019s award for outstanding performance and professional excellence.\u00a0 The Vienna-based Kerala Community gave him a life-time achievement award as a great scholar and gentle helper. A similar life-time achievement award was given to him by the management of Pioneer Kumarasamy College, Nagercoil, where he started his career as a lecturer in 1970, for professional excellence. At the first World Tamil Economic Conference, he was honoured with the coveted award \u201cTamil Crown Jewel of the World\u201d.  He is also the recipient of the 2013 Global Indian Association Award for International Excellence. The KG foundation recently conferred the \u201cDynamic Indian of the Millennium Award\u201d upon him. In October 2018, the Indian Newslink, Auckland, New Zealand, honoured him with a special commemorative  award for his distinguished services to international communities and the Indian Diaspora. \n\nBy a dint  hard work and dedication he won the approbation of many world-wide for  his innovative and practical ideas for fostering sustainable development, with an accent sectoral innovation systems and  social inclusion.   Areas of specialization include new sources of dynamic growth, sustainable sources of livelihoods, and determinants of competitiveness, national industrial innovation systems, private sector development and institutional capacity building for strengthening national and sectoral innovation systems. \nAfter retiring from UNIDO,  he worked briefly for the Asian Development Bank (ADB), as an expert  on cluster networking.  Currently working on the rapidly changing facets of the new industrial revolution, in co-authorship with a few experts, which will soon be published as a book by UNIDO. Recently coined the syllabus for a new subject called \u201cBusiness Futurology\u201d for the students of management.  He briefly served as   an expert for EGMs organized by  the knowledge management unit of the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), Vienna, Austria,  and made scholarly inputs to non-nuclear energy innovation systems. He also worked as a lead consultant for  the UN FAO, Rome, Italy, on an operational strategy paper for fostering agribusiness in Syria and Oman.\n\n== Writings ==\nVinanchiarachi has authored and co-authored more than a hundred articles{{citation needed|date=June 2016}} and reports on industrial growth, South-South cooperation, trade liberalization in South-east Asia and sustainable growth models for newly industrializing countries. Most notable books include:\n\n* ''India's Time''\n* ''Myths and Realities of East Asian Model of Development''\n* ''Demand Analysis''\n* ''Rethinking Development Realities''\n* ''Intervene to Industrialize'' (co-author)\n*   The Poverty of Economic Thinking\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vinanchiarachi, Jebamalai}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "103.204.156.98", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eReferences)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jebamalai_Vinanchiarachi"}
{"title_page": "List of Championship Wrestling From Hollywood personnel", "text_new": "{{short description|Listing of all current personnel of American professional wrestling promotion Championship Wrestling From Hollywood}}\n\n[[Championship Wrestling From Hollywood]] (CWFH) is an American [[professional wrestling promotion]] based in [[Port Hueneme, California]]. Active wrestlers and on-screen talent appear on ''[[Championship Wrestling From Hollywood]]'' and at [[House show|live events]]. Personnel is organized below by their role in Championship Wrestling From Hollywood. Their [[ring name]] is on the left, and their [[Given name|real name]] is on the right. Championship Wrestling From Hollywood refers to its in-ring performers as \"Wrestlers\"\n\nCWFH has promotional partnerships with [[iMPACT Wrestling]]. Wrestlers from those promotions may make occasional appearances on MLW events and programming.\n\n==Roster==\n====Male Wrestlers====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" align=\"left center\" width=\"60%\"\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=\"20%\"|Ring Name \n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=\"20%\"|Real Name\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=\"40%\"|Notes\n|-\n|Adam Thornstowe\n|Adam DeBoor\n|\n|-\n|Adrian Quest\n|''Unknown''\n|\n|-\n|Andy Brown\n|Andrew Minafee\n|\n|-\n|{{sort|Tito|Bad Dude Tito}}\n|Tito Escondido\n|\n|-\n|{{sort|Bateman|Bateman}}\n|{{sort|Croslin, Cody|Cody Croslin}}\n|\n|-\n|Brandon Cutler\n|Brandon Cutler\n|\n|-\n|{{sort|Coach Flex|Coach Flex McCallion}}\n|David McCallion\n|\n|-\n|Chris Bey\n|''Unknown''\n|\n|-\n|D'Marco Wilson\n|''Unknown''\n|\n|-\n|{{sort|Joseph, Dan|Dan Joseph}}\n|''Dan Siejak''\n|\n|-\n|{{sort|Rivera, Danny|Danny Rivera}}\n|Unknown\n|\n|-\n|{{sort|Mayer, Dicky|Dicky Mayer}}\n|Chris Maier\n|\n|-\n|Douglas James\n|''Unknown''\n|\n|-\n|{{sort|Bostic, Dylan|Dylan Bostic}}\n|''Unknown''\n|\n|-\n|{{sort|Drake, Dylan|Dylan Drake}}\n|Drake Younger\n|\n|-\n|{{sort|Watts, Eric|Eric Watts}}\n|Jason Watts\n|\n|-\n|Evan Daniels\n|''Unknown''\n|\n|-\n|Fidel Bravo\n|Fidel Bravo\n|\n|-\n|\n|-\n|{{sort|Hobo|Hobo}} Baines\n|{{sort|Taylor, Brandon|Brandon Taylor}}\n|\n|-\n|{{sort|Morgan, James|James Morgan}}\n|{{sort|Morgan, James|James Morgan}}\n|\n|-\n|{{sort|Jarek 120|Jarek 120}}\n|{{sort|Thomas, Evan|Evan Thomas}}\n|\n|-\n|{{sort|Cottonbelly, Jervis|[[Jervis Cottonbelly]]}}\n|''Unknown''\n|\n|-\n|{{sort|Ryan, Joey|[[Joey Ryan (wrestler)|Joey Ryan]]}}\n|{{sort|Meehan, Joey|Joey Meehan}}\n|\n|-\n|{{sort|Clearwater, Jordan|Jordan Clearwater}}\n|''Unknown''\n|\n|- \n|{{sort|Nelson, Jorel|Jorel Nelson}}\n|''Unknown''\n|\n|-\n|{{sort|Kratos|Kratos}}\n|J R Kratos\n|\n|-\n|Luster the Legend\n|David Luster\n|\n|-\n|{{sort|\"Pistolero\" Julio Pedroza|\"Pistolero\" Julio Pedroza}}\n|{{sort|Julio Pedroza|Julio Pedroza}}\n|\n|-\n|{{sort|Coleman, Julius|Julius Coleman}}\n|''Unknown''\n|\n|-\n|Keegan Brettle\n|\n|\n|-\n|{{sort|Martenson, Kevin|Kevin Martenson}}\n|\n|\n|-\n|{{sort|Blaze, Leo|Leo Blaze}}\n|\n|\n|-\n|{{sort|Aldis, Nick|[[Nick Aldis]]}}\n|\n|[[NWA Worlds Heavyweight Championship|NWA Worlds Heavyweight Champion]]\n|-\n|{{sort|Camden, Mike|Mike Camden}}\n|\n|\n|-\n|{{sort|Avalon, Peter|[[Peter Avalon]]}}\n|\n|\n|-\n|Pentagato\n|\n|\n|-\n|Pinks\n|\n|\n|-\n|R3\n|\n|\n|-\n|{{sort|Raul|Raul}}\n|''Unknown''\n|\n|-\n|Ray Rosas\n|Ray Rosas\n|\n|-\n|Rey Felix\n|''Unknown''\n|\n|-\n|Richie Slade\n|''Unknown''\n|\n|-\n|{{sort|Rojelio|Rojelio}}\n|''Unknown''\n|\n|-\n|{{sort|Romero, Rocky|[[Rocky Romero]]}}\n|{{sort|Rivera, John|John R. Rivera}}\n|\n|-\n|Royce Isaacs\n|''Unknown''\n|[[UWN Television Championship|UWN Television Champion]]\n|-\n|{{sort|Taylor, Ryan|[[Ryan Taylor (wrestler)|Ryan Taylor]]}}\n|{{sort|Taylor, Russell|Russell Taylor}}\n| \n|-\n|{{sort|Darevko, Sasha|Sasha Darevko}}\n|{{sort|Rickert, Brandon|Brandon Rickert}}\n|\n|-\n|{{sort|Scorpio Sky|[[Scorpio Sky]]}}\n|{{sort|Andrews, Schuylar|Shuyler Andrews}}\n|\n|-\n|Stokley Hathaway\n|''Unknown''\n|\n|-\n|Suede Thompson\n|''Unknown