s      = <ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web|url=http://geonames.usgs.gov|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=US Board on Geographic Names|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|date=2007-10-25}}</ref>\n|elevation_m              = 255\n|elevation_ft             = 837\n|coordinates              = {{coord|39|17|11|N|84|31|13|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 45240\n|area_code                = [[Area code 513|513]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 39-27706<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web |url=http://factfinder.census.gov |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212221153/http://factfinder.census.gov/main.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2020-02-12 |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2008-01-31 |title=American FactFinder }}</ref>\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 1040570<ref name=\"GR3\" />\n|website                  = {{URL|www.forestpark.org}}\n|footnotes                = \n}}\n'''Forest Park''' is a city in [[Hamilton County, Ohio|Hamilton County]], [[Ohio]], United States. It is a suburb of [[Cincinnati]]. The population was 18,720 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]].<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{Cite web |url=http://factfinder.census.gov |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212221153/http://factfinder.census.gov/main.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 12, 2020 |title=Profile of General Population and Housing Characteristics: 2010 Demographic Profile Data (DP-1): Forest Park city, Ohio |publisher=U.S. Census Bureau, American Factfinder |accessdate=October 30, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nForest Park is located at {{coord|39|17|11|N|84|31|13|W|type:city}} (39.286408, -84.520363).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|6.48|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, all land.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web |title=US Gazetteer files 2010 |url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2013-01-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120702145235/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |archivedate=2012-07-02 }}</ref>\n\n===Borders===\nForest Park borders the following:\n{|\n|- valign=top\n|\n'''Cities'''\n* [[Fairfield, Ohio|Fairfield]]\n* [[Springdale, Ohio|Springdale]]\n|\n'''Villages'''\n* [[Greenhills, Ohio|Greenhills]]\n|\n'''Townships'''\n* [[Springfield Township, Hamilton County, Ohio|Springfield]]\n* [[Colerain Township, Hamilton County, Ohio|Colerain]]\n|\n'''Counties'''\n* [[Butler County, Ohio|Butler]]\n|}\n\n==History==\nThe City of Forest Park, Ohio was founded in 1956, two years after private developers Marvin Warner and Joseph Kanter purchased 3,400 acres of 5,930 acres north of Cincinnati originally set aside in 1935 by the Resettlement Administration under President Franklin D. Roosevelt to relocate struggling urban and rural families to one of three such communities planned by the government called Greenbelt towns.\n\nThe Greenbelt concept was abandoned in 1949 and the as yet undeveloped acreage of Greenhills, Ohio, which had opened in 1938, became available for purchase by the Warner-Kanter Corporation in 1954. After two years of planning they opened homes for purchase in the first residential area of Forest Park, the C section, in March 1956.\n\nAfter growing to a population of 4800 in 1960 and incorporation as a village in 1961, then achieving city status in 1968, Forest Park intentionally became an \u201copen city,\u201d regularly adopting and passing resolutions and ordinances welcoming citizens regardless of race, creed or national origin, a policy intended to maintain the city\u2019s commitment to diversity.\n\nToward this end, in 1978, the Forest Park Housing Commission created \u201cA Comprehensive Strategy for Maintaining Diversity in Forest Park, \u201cto combat discriminatory practices by realtors, builders and corporations.\u201d<ref>City of Forest Park Housing Commission, \u201cA Comprehensive Strategy for Maintaining Diversity in Forest Park,\u201d Typescript, March, 1978, Forest Park Historical Society Archives.</ref>\n\nAfter a 1980 lawsuit filed by the city against a builder was dismissed for insufficient evidence, the Forest Park council issued a statement declaring that \u201cpeople have the right to choose where to live, work or play based on their own free choice.  That right must be secured for all people and never be artificially restricted.\u201d<ref>Forest Park Council, Resolution No. 30-1982, \u201cExpressing the Policy of the Forest Park City Council with Regard to the Issuance of a \u2018Quality of Integrated Life Statement\u2019 in the City of Forest Park,\u201d passed unanimously April 19, 1982; ''Cincinnati Post'', March 20, 29 and 30, 1982; ''Cincinnati Enquirer'', March 27 and 30 and April 20, 1982; ''Millcreek Valley News'', April 8 and 29, 1982.</ref>\n\nThe Quality of Integrated Life resolution of 1982 would serve as a guide to integrated living, reinforcing the long-held view that diversity was a strength of Forest Park as the city moved toward a new century. In 1991 this view was reinforced when a Quality of Life Task Force issued a vision statement reflecting the \u201cshared values of a multicultural citizenry.\u201d<ref>''The New Times'', April 20, 1991.</ref>\n\nIn the minds of its residents and outsiders, Forest Park\u2019s commitment to diversity in an open community became a model for 21st century living.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1970= 15139\n|1980= 18770\n|1990= 18609\n|2000= 19463\n|2010= 18720\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=18678\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 5, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426102944/http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|archivedate=April 26, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===2010 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name =\"FactFinder\">{{cite web|title=American FactFinder|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212234628/http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml|url-status=dead|archive-date=2020-02-12|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2013-01-06}}</ref> of 2010, there were 18,720 people, 7,212 households, and 4,924 families living in the city. The [[population density]] was {{convert|2888.9|PD/sqmi|PD/km2|1}}. There were 7,854 housing units at an average density of {{convert|1212.0|/sqmi|/km2|1}}. The racial makeup of the city was 24.9% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 65.0% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.2% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 2.2% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.2% [[Race (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 3.9% from [[Race (U.S. Census)|other races]], and 3.6% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 6.4% of the population.\n\nThere were 7,212 households of which 35.8% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 40.8% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 21.9% had a female householder with no husband present, 5.5% had a male householder with no wife present, and 31.7% were non-families. 26.6% of all households were made up of individuals and 7.3% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.59 and the average family size was 3.13.\n\nThe median age in the city was 35.8 years. 26.9% of residents were under the age of 18; 9.1% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 26.2% were from 25 to 44; 26% were from 45 to 64; and 11.7% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the city was 46.4% male and 53.6% female.\n\n===2000 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2000, there were 19,463 people, 7,505 households, and 5,238 families living in the city. The [[population density]] was 2,990.4 people per square mile (1,154.3/km\u00b2). There were 7,748 housing units at an average density of 1,190.4 per square mile (459.5/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 36.70% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 56.26% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.11% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 3.67% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.08% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.99% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 2.20% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 1.48% of the population.\n\nThere were 7,505 households out of which 34.0% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 50.4% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 15.6% had a female householder with no husband present, and 30.2% were non-families. 24.9% of all households were made up of individuals and 5.3% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.58 and the average family size was 3.12.\n\nIn the city the population was spread out with 27.1% under the age of 18, 8.4% from 18 to 24, 31.9% from 25 to 44, 23.6% from 45 to 64, and 9.1% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 34 years. For every 100 females, there were 92.3 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 88.0 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $49,298, and the median income for a family was $55,618. Males had a median income of $38,682 versus $28,454 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $21,820. About 5.1% of families and 6.0% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 8.2% of those under age 18 and 7.3% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Education==\nThe [[Winton Woods City School District]] covers most of Forest Park, along with Greenhills and Springfield Township.\n\n<!--Should refer to private schools in within the city limits, if any, not regional private-schooling options:\nForest Park and the surrounding areas also have several private school options, both on the elementary and high school levels. Several Catholic institutions supply the area with quality parochial education. On the elementary level, St. James of the Valley, in Wyoming; Sacred Heart School, in Fairfield; and St. Vivian school and St. Bartholomew School, both in Finneytown, provide K-8 schooling. On the high school level, Badin High School in Hamilton and Roger Bacon High School in St. Bernard offer co-ed 9-12 education, while McAuley High School in College Hill, St. Ursula Academy in East Walnut Hills and Mt. Notre Dame High School on Columbia Avenue offer all-girls 9-12 education and St. Xavier High School and Lasalle High School, both on North Bend Road, and Moeller High School in Blue Ash offer all-boys 9-12 education.\n...end comment-->\n\nForest Park is served by a branch of the [[Public Library of Cincinnati and Hamilton County]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cincinnatilibrary.org/branches/forestpark.html | title=Forest Park Branch | publisher=Public Library of Cincinnati and Hamilton County | accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.forestpark.org City website]\n* [http://www.wintonwoods.org Winton Woods City School District]\n* [http://www.waycross.org Waycross Community Media] for Forest Park area\n\n{{Hamilton County, Ohio}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Hamilton County, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Cities in Ohio]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forest_Park,_Ohio"}
{"title_page": "Carson Kreitzer", "text_new": "{{External links|date=June 2014}}\n\n'''Carson Kreitzer''' is an American playwright currently based in [[Minneapolis]], Minnesota. She graduated [[magna cum laude]] from [[Yale University]] in 1991<ref>{{cite web|url=http://enquirer.com/editions/2002/08/13/tem_rosenthal_winner_set.html|title=Rosenthal winner set in Cold War|accessdate=June 25, 2014|work=Cincinnati Enquirer|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|date=August 13, 2002|first=Jackie |last=Demaline}}</ref> with a B.A. in theatre and literature and an M.F.A. from the [[Michener Center for Writers]] at the [[University of Texas, Austin]].\n\nKreitizer is an associated artist with [[Clubbed Thumb]], [[New Georges]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newgeorges.org/|title=New Georges -|website=New Georges}}</ref> the Fire Department,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thefiredept.org/index.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227161852/http://thefiredept.org/index.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=27 February 2014|title=The Fire Dept.|date=27 February 2014}}</ref> and [[Park Square Theatre, Boston|Park Square Theatre]], and was a resident playwright with [[New Dramatists]] from 2006-2013. She is a member of the [[The Playwrights' Center|Workhaus Collective]], the [[Dramatists Guild]], and [[The Playwrights' Center]] where, in 2013, she became a board member.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwcenter.org/news.php?n=152|title=The Playwrights' Center Welcomes New Board Members|accessdate=June 25, 2014|publisher=The Playwrights\u2019 Center|date=November 26, 2013}}</ref>\nHer plays ''The Love Song of [[J. Robert Oppenheimer]]'' and ''Self Defense, or death of some salesmen'' are published in the Smith and Kraus collections ''Women Playwrights: Best Plays of'' 2004 and 2002 respectively.,  and the plays ''Self Defense'', ''Oppenheimer'', ''1:23'', and ''Slither'' are available in one volume from NoPassport Press<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nopassport.org/Press|title=Publications - NoPassport|website=nopassport.org|access-date=2014-06-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017155135/http://nopassport.org/Press|archive-date=2014-10-17|url-status=dead}}</ref> (2011).\n\n== Full-length plays ==\n{{MOSLOW|date=August 2014}}\n*''Heroin/e (Keep Us Quiet)'' (1995) is the first play in Kreitzer's ''Women Who Kill'' triptych featuring intertwined monologues spoken by two characters: Anna, the older sister of [[Sigmund Freud]]'s famous patient, the [[Sergei Pankejeff|Wolf Man]], who committed suicide by drinking mercury in 1906 and [[Ellie Nesler]], a woman who shot her son's accused molester as he was testifying in court.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/04/04/us/accused-molester-is-killed-in-court.html | title=Accused Molester is Killed in Court | work=New York Times | date=April 4, 1993 |location=Jamestown, California | accessdate=December 30, 2015}}</ref> NYC premiere by Tiny Mythic Theatre. \n*''The Slow Drag'' (1996) a \"jazz cabaret\" with a live band onstage, which features the character, Johnny Christmas, performing the story of his life, a story that reflects that of American jazz musician [[Billy Tipton]], whose successful career as a male crooner made headlines upon his death when it was revealed he was actually a woman. \n*''Freakshow'' (1999) published in the Playscripts anthology ''Funny, Strange, Provocative: Seven Plays From Clubbed Thumb''\n*''Valerie Shoots Andy'' (2001) is the second Women Who Kill play and takes a close look at [[Valerie Solanas]], author of the [[S.C.U.M. Manifesto]] and best known for shooting artist [[Andy Warhol]] in 1968. NYC Premiere by Reverie Productions at the Present Company Theatorium in NYC. Earlier version workshopped in 1993 at American Place Theatre by 40 Feet Under.\n*''Self Defense, or death of some salesmen'' (2002) is the final play of Women Who Kill, recounting the story of [[Aileen Wuornos]], who was convicted of shooting six men along Florida's interstate highways in the early 1990s. It depicts the media frenzy surrounding her identification, capture and conviction but with a sympathetic eye towards Wuornos' claims of self-defense at the hands of violent clients she serviced as a prostitute. NYC Premiere by Reverie Productions with New Georges at [[HERE Arts Center]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.reverieproductions.org/Reverie%20Site%20031207/pages/past_seasons.html |title=Past Seasons |accessdate=June 25, 2014 |publisher=Reverie Productions |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080624194426/http://www.reverieproductions.org/Reverie%20Site%20031207/pages/past_seasons.html |archivedate=June 24, 2008 }}</ref>\n*''The Love Song of [[J. Robert Oppenheimer]]'' (2003) was nominated for the Pulitzer Prize in Drama and won the 2003 Lois and Richard Rosenthal New Play Prize, the American Theatre Critics\u2019 Steinberg Citation, and the Barrie Stavis Award. Notable productions Actor's Express (Atlanta, GA) April 2005.<ref>{{cite web \n |url=http://www.actors-express.com/cgi-bin/MySQLdb?VIEW=/plays/viewone.txt&myplay=4 \n |title=The Love Song of J. Robert Oppenheimer \n |accessdate=June 25, 2014 \n |publisher=Actor's Express \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012080337/http://www.actors-express.com/cgi-bin/MySQLdb?VIEW=%2Fplays%2Fviewone.txt&myplay=4 \n |archivedate=October 12, 2007 \n }}</ref>\n*''Slither'' (2003) chronicles five generations of women, from Eve to a contemporary Christian snake-cult member, linked together through their relationship with snakes. 2003 premiere produced by Eye of the Storm Theatre at Minneapolis Theatre Garage (Minneapolis, MN).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.talkinbroadway.com/regional/minn/minn50.html|title=Minneapolis|accessdate=June 25, 2014|first=Elizabeth|last=Weir|publisher=Talkin' Broadway}}</ref> Received its West coast premiere in 2012 by Chalk Repertory<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chalkrep.com|title=CHALK REPERTORY THEATRE - classical and contemporary plays in unconventional spaces|website=www.chalkrep.com}}</ref> with a staging at the Masonic Lodge inside [[Hollywood Forever Cemetery]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://laist.com/2012/02/18/snake_love_story_slither_at_hollywo.php|title=Snake Love Story: 'Slither' at Hollywood Forever Cemetery|accessdate=June 25, 2014|first=Mia|last=Bonadonna|date=February 18, 2012|publisher=laist.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171106092545/http://laist.com/2012/02/18/snake_love_story_slither_at_hollywo.php|archivedate=November 6, 2017}}\n</ref>\n* ''Caravaggista'' traces the early life of the [[baroque]] artist [[Artemisia Gentileschi]] and focuses on the events surrounding the rape trial brought by her father against [[Agostino Tassi]], another artist he had hired to teach his daughter Perspective. Throughout the play Artemisia is guided by the spirit of [[Caravaggio]] as she develops her masterwork ''[[Judith Slaying Holofernes]]''.  This play was workshopped at [[The Public Theater]] in New York.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newdramatists.org/carson-kreitzer/caravaggista|title=Caravaggista|accessdate=June 25, 2014|publisher=New Dramatists}}</ref>\n*''Flesh and the Desert'' (2005) originally commissioned by Clubbed Thumb with a premiere as part of the 2005 [[David Mark Cohen]] New Works Festival,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/arts/2005-04-08/265647/|title=University Co-op Presents the 2005 David Mark Cohen New Works Festival|accessdate=June 25, 2014|first= Robert|last= Faires|date=April 8, 2005|work=[[The Austin Chronicle]]}}</ref> this play is a kaleidoscopic portrait of Las Vegas featuring showgirls, gangsters, Siegfried and Roy, Elvis, Liberace, nuclear testing, Orson Welles, and the intertwined stories of three couples. Produced in 2012 by the Workhaus Collective and performed at The Playwright's Center in Minneapolis, MN making the Top 10 of 2012 list by the ''Star Tribune'' theater critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/entertainment/stageandarts/184435371.html?refer=y#AQcLwpSbX5bRPDIk.97|title=Small theaters made big impression|accessdate=June 25, 2014|work=StarTrubune|first= Rohan|last= Preston|first2= Graydon|last2= Royce|date=December 24, 2012}}</ref>\n* ''1:23'' (2007) a \"theatrical collage\" about infamous cases of contemporary infanticide and the public's obsession with women who kill. The play uses characters from the annals of true crime, specifically [[Susan Smith]], [[Andrea Yates]], and the lesser-known Juana Leija.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0203/14/ltm.12.html|title=CNN.com - Transcripts|website=transcripts.cnn.com}}</ref> Premiered at [[Cincinnati Playhouse in the Park]]'s Thompson Shelterhouse theater space in Feb. 2007, directed by Mark Wing-Davey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/105421-Unthinkable-Crimes-by-Parents-Conjured-in-World-Premiere-123-in-Cincinnati |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140625155849/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/105421-Unthinkable-Crimes-by-Parents-Conjured-in-World-Premiere-123-in-Cincinnati |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 25, 2014 |title=Unthinkable Crimes by Parents Conjured in World Premiere, 1:23, in Cincinnati |accessdate=June 25, 2014 |first=Kenneth |last=Jones |date=February 3, 2007 |work=Playbill }}</ref> Notable productions at Synchronicity Performance Group<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.synchrotheatre.com/|title=Synchronicity: Smart. Gutsy. Bold. Theatre.|website=www.synchrotheatre.com}}</ref> (Atlanta, GA) in May 2009, Perishable Theatre (Providence, RI) in May 2011. \n*''Enchantment'' (2009) \n*''Behind the Eye'' (2011) chronicles the career and private life of surrealist muse/model and WWII combat photographer [[Lee Miller]]. Premiered at [[Cincinnati Playhouse]] in Apr. 2011, directed by [[Mark Wing-Davey]] and the production was nominated for 8 Acclaim Awards<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20140817183558/http://www.cinstages.com/Acclaim/index.asp</ref> from the League of Cincinnati Theatres for its direction, acting, and design. Notable productions at Gas & Electric Arts (Philadelphia, PA) in Oct. 2012,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gasandelectricarts.org/Gas_%26_Electric_Arts/Behind_the_Eye_Photos.html|title=Behind the Eye: Photos|accessdate=June 25, 2014|publisher=Gas & Electric Arts}}</ref> Park Square Theatre (St. Paul, MN) in May 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parksquaretheatre.org/www/pst-showpage-eye.php |title=Behind the Eye |accessdate=June 25, 2014 |publisher=Park Square Theatre |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140607021458/http://www.parksquaretheatre.org/www/pst-showpage-eye.php |archivedate=June 7, 2014 }}</ref>\n* ''Lasso of Truth'' (2014) commissioned by the National New Play Network<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nnpn.org|title=Home - National New Play Network|website=www.nnpn.org}}</ref> for a rolling premiere in the 2014-15 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nnpn.org/news/nnpn-announces-the-40th-rolling-world-premiere-lasso-of-truth-by-carson-kreitzer|title=NNPN Announces the 40th Rolling World Premiere: Lasso of Truth \u2013 by Carson Kreitzer|accessdate=June 25, 2014|date=August 16, 2013|publisher=National New Play Network|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131106060504/http://www.nnpn.org/news/nnpn-announces-the-40th-rolling-world-premiere-lasso-of-truth-by-carson-kreitzer|archivedate=November 6, 2013}}</ref> This \"multimedia theatrical event explores the history of [[Wonder Woman]] \u2013 from her creation as a comic book superhero character to her lasting influence in American pop culture\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://marintheatre.org/press/press-releases/lasso-of-truth-world-premiere/|title=Lasso of Truth: World Premier|date=January 23, 2014|accessdate=June 25, 2014|publisher=Marin Theatre Company}}</ref> Workshop reading at National Play Festival (Australia) Feb. 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwa.org.au/lasso-of-truth/|title=lasso of truth by carson kreitzer (us)|accessdate=June 25, 2014|date=February 23, 2014|publisher=playwriting australia|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810111604/http://www.pwa.org.au/lasso-of-truth/|archive-date=August 10, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Premiered February. 2014 at [[Marin Theatre]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://marintheatre.org/productions/lasso/|title=Lasso of Truth|accessdate=June 25, 2014|publisher=Marin Theatre Company}}</ref> (Mill Valley, CA), November 2014 at Synchronicity Performance Group (Atlanta, GA),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.synchrotheatre.com/season/lasso-of-truth|title=Lasso of Truth|accessdate=June 25, 2014|publisher=Synchronicity}}</ref> and January 2015 at the [[Unicorn Theatre (Kansas City)]] in Missouri.\n\n== Awards and Grants ==\n\n*2001-2002 McKnight Advancement Grant, Playwright's Center (Minneapolis, MN).\n*2003-2004 [[Susan Smith Blackburn Prize]] in playwriting. \n*2007 Playwrights Of New York (PONY) Fellowship at the [[Lark Play Development Center]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playwrightsofnewyork.org/playwrights.html|title=Meet the PoNYs|accessdate=June 25, 2014|publisher=Playwrights Of New York}}</ref>\n*2008 \\\"Core Writers\\\" award from The Ruth Easton Lab at The Playwright's Center (Minneapolis).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwcenter.org/news.php?n=3|title=Prestigious \\\"Core Writer\\\" Distinction Awarded|accessdate=June 25, 2014|publisher=The Playwright's Center}}</ref>\n*2014 Joe Dowling Annaghmakerrig Fellowship through [[Guthrie Theatre]] and the Tyrone Guthrie Center at Annaghmakerrig, Ireland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/entertainment/blogs/235488071.html#4tcBPmUDu7dLklBm.97|title=Playwright Carson Kreitzer wins Dowling fellowship|accessdate=June 25, 2014|first= Rohan |last=Preston|date=December 11, 2013|work=StarTribune}}</ref>\n*2016 [[Jonathan Larson]] Grant from the [[American Theatre Wing]]\n*2017 [[MacDowell Colony]] Fellowship<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://macdow.convio.net/site/PageNavigator/2017Jan74WinterSpringFellowsPicked.html|title=MacDowell Fellowships Awarded to 74 Artists in Multiple Disciplines - The MacDowell Colony|website=macdow.convio.net|access-date=2017-08-17}}</ref>\n\n== Reviews ==\n\n*''Lasso of Truth'' from ''San Francisco Gate'': The women are potent and the guys like it like that in Carson Kreitzer's Lasso of Truth, and that seems fitting for a play about [[Wonder Woman]]. Not that the world's premier female superhero makes any direct appearances in the world premiere that opened Tuesday at Marin Theatre Company, but aspects of her infuse the generations of feminists who inspired and were inspired by her in an idea-packed and brilliantly cartoon-enhanced play.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/performance/article/Wonder-Woman-would-approve-Lasso-of-Truth-5270112.php|title='Lasso of Truth' review: Wonder Woman and a 3-way|accessdate=June 25, 2014|work=SFGate|date=March 1, 2014|first=Robert |last=Hurwitt}}</ref>\n*''Behind the Eye'' from ''City Beat Cincinnati'': According to Carson Kreitzer's new script, Behind the Eye, premiering at the Cincinnati Playhouse, Lee Miller 'reflects light so well it seems that she herself is the source.' Miller, you see, is a forgotten but real historical figure, a photographer's model in Vogue in the 1920s, a photographer herself in the 1930s and a fearless photojournalist across Europe during World War II. By any standards she was promiscuous and willful, a free spirit for whom happiness was just beyond her grasp. She is the fascinating focal point for Kreitzer's compelling new play [...], perhaps the best piece of theater at the Playhouse this season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://citybeat.com/cincinnati/article-23063-behind-the-eye-(review).html|title=Behind the Eye (Review)|accessdate=June 25, 2014|first=Rick|last=Pender|date=April 11, 2011|work=CityBeat|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140707155448/http://citybeat.com/cincinnati/article-23063-behind-the-eye-(review).html|archive-date=July 7, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*''1:23'' from Atlanta's ''Creative Loafing'': Playwright Carson Kreitzer's drama draws on elements of police procedurals like Law & Order in its investigation of the crimes of Susan Smith and two other notorious mothers who killed their children. In 1:23, we know whodunit, so the more pressing question becomes, 'Why did they do it?' Kreitzer's script finds clues in official records, urban legends and Latin-American folklore, placing the killings in complex, almost baffling cultural and psychological contexts. [...] Few themes prove as big or challenging as the ones raised in 1:23. If anything, the play's ambition nearly overleaps itself in its attempt to address too many ideas in too limited a time. 1:23 serves as a harrowing thematic symphony that can be overly pretentious and opaque, yet also builds to some genuine revelations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://clatl.com/atlanta/synchronicitys-123-medea-blitz/Content?oid=1279465|title=Synchronicity's 1:23 Medea blitz |accessdate=June 25, 2014|publisher=Creative Loafing Atlanta|date=April 20, 2009|first=Curt |last=Holman}}</ref>\n*''Valerie Shoots Andy'' from ''[[The New York Times]]'': Ms. Kreitzer offers an assessment of how Solanas's play (''Up Your Ass'') and a diatribe she wrote shortly before the shooting called the SCUM manifesto evolved into gunshots. It is a bleak but fascinating piece that plays with Warhol's notions of repetition, returning to the shooting and its immediate aftermath again and again as it fleshes out the portrait of Solanas, who died in 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/03/01/theater/theater-review-writer-one-day-would-be-killer-next-reliving-warhol-shooting.html|title=Theater Review \u2014 A Writer One Day, a Would-Be Killer the Next: Reliving the Warhol Shooting|accessdate=June 25, 2014|work=[[The New York Times]]|date= March 1, 2001|first=Neil |last=Genzlinger}}</ref>\n\n== In Development ==\n\n* ''Runway 69'' a new musical, \"a provocative story of one of the raunchiest strip clubs in mid-1990s Times Square, and the lives of the men and women who work there.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.erinkamler.net/musicals/runway-69/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140625155856/http://www.erinkamler.net/musicals/runway-69/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 25, 2014 |title=Runway 69 |accessdate=June 25, 2014 |publisher=Erin Kamler }}</ref> Workshopped at the 2013 The Ground Floor<ref>{{cite web|url=http://berkeleyrep.org/groundfloor/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505020903/http://berkeleyrep.org/groundfloor/|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 May 2014|title=The Ground Floor at Berkeley Rep|date=5 May 2014}}</ref> summer residency lab at [[Berkeley Rep]]. Book and lyrics by Krietzer; Music, Lyrics, and original concept by Erin Kamler.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.erinkamler.net/bio/|title=Bio|publisher=}}</ref>\n* ''Lempicka'' a new musical inspired by \"the tempestuous life of [[Art Deco]] artist [[Tamara de Lempicka]].\" Commissioned by [[Yale Rep]] and New Dramatists. Book and lyrics by Krietzer; music by composer Matt Gould.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newdramatists.org/events/2012-10-29/full-stage-usa-carson-kreitzer|title=Full Stage USA: Carson Kreitzer|accessdate=June 25, 2014|publisher=New Dramatists}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.carsonkreitzer.com}}\n* [http://newdramatists.org/carson-kreitzer Carson Kreitzer at New Dramatists]\n* [http://www.playscripts.com/author.php3?authorid=276 Carson Kreitzer at Playscripts, Inc.]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130806174824/http://www.workhauscollective.org/Site/Now.html Workhaus Collective]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140607021458/http://www.parksquaretheatre.org/www/pst-showpage-eye.php Carson Kreitzer at Doollee.com]\n* [http://americantheatrewing.org/recipients/carson-kreitzer/ Carson Kreitzer's Jonathan Larson Grant performance]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kreitzer, Carson}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Michener Center for Writers alumni]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{External links|date=June 2014}}\n\n'''Carson Kreitzer''' is an American playwright currently based in [[Minneapolis]], Minnesota. She graduated [[magna cum laude]] from [[Yale University]] in 1991<ref>{{cite web|url=http://enquirer.com/editions/2002/08/13/tem_rosenthal_winner_set.html|title=Rosenthal winner set in Cold War|accessdate=June 25, 2014|work=Cincinnati Enquirer|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|date=August 13, 2002|first=Jackie |last=Demaline}}</ref> with a B.A. in theatre and literature and an M.F.A. from the [[Michener Center for Writers]] at the [[University of Texas, Austin]].\n\nKreitizer is an associated artist with [[Clubbed Thumb]], [[New Georges]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newgeorges.org/|title=New Georges -|website=New Georges}}</ref> the Fire Department,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thefiredept.org/index.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227161852/http://thefiredept.org/index.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=27 February 2014|title=The Fire Dept.|date=27 February 2014}}</ref> and [[Park Square Theatre, Boston|Park Square Theatre]], and was a resident playwright with [[New Dramatists]] from 2006-2013. She is a member of the [[The Playwrights' Center|Workhaus Collective]], the [[Dramatists Guild]], and [[The Playwrights' Center]] where, in 2013, she became a board member.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwcenter.org/news.php?n=152|title=The Playwrights' Center Welcomes New Board Members|accessdate=June 25, 2014|publisher=The Playwrights\u2019 Center|date=November 26, 2013}}</ref>\nHer plays ''The Love Song of [[J. Robert Oppenheimer]]'' and ''Self Defense, or death of some salesmen'' are published in the Smith and Kraus collections ''Women Playwrights: Best Plays of'' 2004 and 2002 respectively.,  and the plays ''Self Defense'', ''Oppenheimer'', ''1:23'', and ''Slither'' are available in one volume from NoPassport Press<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nopassport.org/Press|title=Publications - NoPassport|website=nopassport.org|access-date=2014-06-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017155135/http://nopassport.org/Press|archive-date=2014-10-17|url-status=dead}}</ref> (2011).\n\n== Full-length plays ==\n{{MOSLOW|date=August 2014}}\n*''Heroin/e (Keep Us Quiet)'' (1995) is the first play in Kreitzer's ''Women Who Kill'' triptych featuring intertwined monologues spoken by two characters: Anna, the older sister of [[Sigmund Freud]]'s famous patient, the [[Sergei Pankejeff|Wolf Man]], who committed suicide by drinking mercury in 1906 and [[Ellie Nesler]], a woman who shot her son's accused molester as he was testifying in court.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/04/04/us/accused-molester-is-killed-in-court.html | title=Accused Molester is Killed in Court | work=New York Times | date=April 4, 1993 |location=Jamestown, California | accessdate=December 30, 2015}}</ref> NYC premiere by Tiny Mythic Theatre. \n*''The Slow Drag'' (1996) a \"jazz cabaret\" with a live band onstage, which features the character, Johnny Christmas, performing the story of his life, a story that reflects that of American jazz musician [[Billy Tipton]], whose successful career as a male crooner made headlines upon his death when it was revealed he was actually a woman. \n*''Freakshow'' (1999) published in the Playscripts anthology ''Funny, Strange, Provocative: Seven Plays From Clubbed Thumb''\n*''Valerie Shoots Andy'' (2001) is the second Women Who Kill play and takes a close look at [[Valerie Solanas]], author of the [[S.C.U.M. Manifesto]] and best known for shooting artist [[Andy Warhol]] in 1968. NYC Premiere by Reverie Productions at the Present Company Theatorium in NYC. Earlier version workshopped in 1993 at American Place Theatre by 40 Feet Under.\n*''Self Defense, or death of some salesmen'' (2002) is the final play of Women Who Kill, recounting the story of [[Aileen Wuornos]], who was convicted of shooting six men along Florida's interstate highways in the early 1990s. It depicts the media frenzy surrounding her identification, capture and conviction but with a sympathetic eye towards Wuornos' claims of self-defense at the hands of violent clients she serviced as a prostitute. NYC Premiere by Reverie Productions with New Georges at [[HERE Arts Center]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.reverieproductions.org/Reverie%20Site%20031207/pages/past_seasons.html |title=Past Seasons |accessdate=June 25, 2014 |publisher=Reverie Productions |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080624194426/http://www.reverieproductions.org/Reverie%20Site%20031207/pages/past_seasons.html |archivedate=June 24, 2008 }}</ref>\n*''The Love Song of [[J. Robert Oppenheimer]]'' (2003) was nominated for the Pulitzer Prize in Drama and won the 2003 Lois and Richard Rosenthal New Play Prize, the American Theatre Critics\u2019 Steinberg Citation, and the Barrie Stavis Award. Notable productions Actor's Express (Atlanta, GA) April 2005.<ref>{{cite web \n |url=http://www.actors-express.com/cgi-bin/MySQLdb?VIEW=/plays/viewone.txt&myplay=4 \n |title=The Love Song of J. Robert Oppenheimer \n |accessdate=June 25, 2014 \n |publisher=Actor's Express \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012080337/http://www.actors-express.com/cgi-bin/MySQLdb?VIEW=%2Fplays%2Fviewone.txt&myplay=4 \n |archivedate=October 12, 2007 \n }}</ref>\n*''Slither'' (2003) chronicles five generations of women, from Eve to a contemporary Christian snake-cult member, linked together through their relationship with snakes. 2003 premiere produced by Eye of the Storm Theatre at Minneapolis Theatre Garage (Minneapolis, MN).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.talkinbroadway.com/regional/minn/minn50.html|title=Minneapolis|accessdate=June 25, 2014|first=Elizabeth|last=Weir|publisher=Talkin' Broadway}}</ref> Received its West coast premiere in 2012 by Chalk Repertory<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chalkrep.com|title=CHALK REPERTORY THEATRE - classical and contemporary plays in unconventional spaces|website=www.chalkrep.com}}</ref> with a staging at the Masonic Lodge inside [[Hollywood Forever Cemetery]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://laist.com/2012/02/18/snake_love_story_slither_at_hollywo.php|title=Snake Love Story: 'Slither' at Hollywood Forever Cemetery|accessdate=June 25, 2014|first=Mia|last=Bonadonna|date=February 18, 2012|publisher=laist.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171106092545/http://laist.com/2012/02/18/snake_love_story_slither_at_hollywo.php|archivedate=November 6, 2017}}\n</ref>\n* ''Caravaggista'' traces the early life of the [[baroque]] artist [[Artemisia Gentileschi]] and focuses on the events surrounding the rape trial brought by her father against [[Agostino Tassi]], another artist he had hired to teach his daughter Perspective. Throughout the play Artemisia is guided by the spirit of [[Caravaggio]] as she develops her masterwork ''[[Judith Slaying Holofernes]]''.  This play was workshopped at [[The Public Theater]] in New York.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newdramatists.org/carson-kreitzer/caravaggista|title=Caravaggista|accessdate=June 25, 2014|publisher=New Dramatists}}</ref>\n*''Flesh and the Desert'' (2005) originally commissioned by Clubbed Thumb with a premiere as part of the 2005 [[David Mark Cohen]] New Works Festival,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/arts/2005-04-08/265647/|title=University Co-op Presents the 2005 David Mark Cohen New Works Festival|accessdate=June 25, 2014|first= Robert|last= Faires|date=April 8, 2005|work=[[The Austin Chronicle]]}}</ref> this play is a kaleidoscopic portrait of Las Vegas featuring showgirls, gangsters, Siegfried and Roy, Elvis, Liberace, nuclear testing, Orson Welles, and the intertwined stories of three couples. Produced in 2012 by the Workhaus Collective and performed at The Playwright's Center in Minneapolis, MN making the Top 10 of 2012 list by the ''Star Tribune'' theater critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/entertainment/stageandarts/184435371.html?refer=y#AQcLwpSbX5bRPDIk.97|title=Small theaters made big impression|accessdate=June 25, 2014|work=StarTrubune|first= Rohan|last= Preston|first2= Graydon|last2= Royce|date=December 24, 2012}}</ref>\n* ''1:23'' (2007) a \"theatrical collage\" about infamous cases of contemporary infanticide and the public's obsession with women who kill. The play uses characters from the annals of true crime, specifically [[Susan Smith]], [[Andrea Yates]], and the lesser-known Juana Leija.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0203/14/ltm.12.html|title=CNN.com - Transcripts|website=transcripts.cnn.com}}</ref> Premiered at [[Cincinnati Playhouse in the Park]]'s Thompson Shelterhouse theater space in Feb. 2007, directed by Mark Wing-Davey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/105421-Unthinkable-Crimes-by-Parents-Conjured-in-World-Premiere-123-in-Cincinnati |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140625155849/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/105421-Unthinkable-Crimes-by-Parents-Conjured-in-World-Premiere-123-in-Cincinnati |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 25, 2014 |title=Unthinkable Crimes by Parents Conjured in World Premiere, 1:23, in Cincinnati |accessdate=June 25, 2014 |first=Kenneth |last=Jones |date=February 3, 2007 |work=Playbill }}</ref> Notable productions at Synchronicity Performance Group<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.synchrotheatre.com/|title=Synchronicity: Smart. Gutsy. Bold. Theatre.|website=www.synchrotheatre.com}}</ref> (Atlanta, GA) in May 2009, Perishable Theatre (Providence, RI) in May 2011. \n*''Enchantment'' (2009) \n*''Behind the Eye'' (2011) chronicles the career and private life of surrealist muse/model and WWII combat photographer [[Lee Miller]]. Premiered at [[Cincinnati Playhouse]] in Apr. 2011, directed by [[Mark Wing-Davey]] and the production was nominated for 8 Acclaim Awards<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20140817183558/http://www.cinstages.com/Acclaim/index.asp</ref> from the League of Cincinnati Theatres for its direction, acting, and design. Notable productions at Gas & Electric Arts (Philadelphia, PA) in Oct. 2012,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gasandelectricarts.org/Gas_%26_Electric_Arts/Behind_the_Eye_Photos.html|title=Behind the Eye: Photos|accessdate=June 25, 2014|publisher=Gas & Electric Arts}}</ref> Park Square Theatre (St. Paul, MN) in May 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parksquaretheatre.org/www/pst-showpage-eye.php |title=Behind the Eye |accessdate=June 25, 2014 |publisher=Park Square Theatre |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140607021458/http://www.parksquaretheatre.org/www/pst-showpage-eye.php |archivedate=June 7, 2014 }}</ref>\n* ''Lasso of Truth'' (2014) commissioned by the National New Play Network<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nnpn.org|title=Home - National New Play Network|website=www.nnpn.org}}</ref> for a rolling premiere in the 2014-15 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nnpn.org/news/nnpn-announces-the-40th-rolling-world-premiere-lasso-of-truth-by-carson-kreitzer|title=NNPN Announces the 40th Rolling World Premiere: Lasso of Truth \u2013 by Carson Kreitzer|accessdate=June 25, 2014|date=August 16, 2013|publisher=National New Play Network|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131106060504/http://www.nnpn.org/news/nnpn-announces-the-40th-rolling-world-premiere-lasso-of-truth-by-carson-kreitzer|archivedate=November 6, 2013}}</ref> This \"multimedia theatrical event explores the history of [[Wonder Woman]] \u2013 from her creation as a comic book superhero character to her lasting influence in American pop culture\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://marintheatre.org/press/press-releases/lasso-of-truth-world-premiere/|title=Lasso of Truth: World Premier|date=January 23, 2014|accessdate=June 25, 2014|publisher=Marin Theatre Company}}</ref> Workshop reading at National Play Festival (Australia) Feb. 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwa.org.au/lasso-of-truth/|title=lasso of truth by carson kreitzer (us)|accessdate=June 25, 2014|date=February 23, 2014|publisher=playwriting australia|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810111604/http://www.pwa.org.au/lasso-of-truth/|archive-date=August 10, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Premiered February. 2014 at [[Marin Theatre]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://marintheatre.org/productions/lasso/|title=Lasso of Truth|accessdate=June 25, 2014|publisher=Marin Theatre Company}}</ref> (Mill Valley, CA), November 2014 at Synchronicity Performance Group (Atlanta, GA),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.synchrotheatre.com/season/lasso-of-truth|title=Lasso of Truth|accessdate=June 25, 2014|publisher=Synchronicity}}</ref> and January 2015 at the [[Unicorn Theatre (Kansas City)]] in Missouri.\n\n== Awards and Grants ==\n\n*2001-2002 McKnight Advancement Grant, Playwright's Center (Minneapolis, MN).\n*2003-2004 [[Susan Smith Blackburn Prize]] in playwriting. \n*2007 Playwrights Of New York (PONY) Fellowship at the [[Lark Play Development Center]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playwrightsofnewyork.org/playwrights.html|title=Meet the PoNYs|accessdate=June 25, 2014|publisher=Playwrights Of New York}}</ref>\n*2008 \\\"Core Writers\\\" award from The Ruth Easton Lab at The Playwright's Center (Minneapolis).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwcenter.org/news.php?n=3|title=Prestigious \\\"Core Writer\\\" Distinction Awarded|accessdate=June 25, 2014|publisher=The Playwright's Center}}</ref>\n*2014 Joe Dowling Annaghmakerrig Fellowship through [[Guthrie Theatre]] and the Tyrone Guthrie Center at Annaghmakerrig, Ireland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/entertainment/blogs/235488071.html#4tcBPmUDu7dLklBm.97|title=Playwright Carson Kreitzer wins Dowling fellowship|accessdate=June 25, 2014|first= Rohan |last=Preston|date=December 11, 2013|work=StarTribune}}</ref>\n*2016 [[Jonathan Larson]] Grant from the [[American Theatre Wing]]\n*2017 [[MacDowell Colony]] Fellowship<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://macdow.convio.net/site/PageNavigator/2017Jan74WinterSpringFellowsPicked.html|title=MacDowell Fellowships Awarded to 74 Artists in Multiple Disciplines - The MacDowell Colony|website=macdow.convio.net|access-date=2017-08-17}}</ref>\n\n== Reviews ==\n\n*''Lasso of Truth'' from ''San Francisco Gate'': The women are potent and the guys like it like that in Carson Kreitzer's Lasso of Truth, and that seems fitting for a play about [[Wonder Woman]]. Not that the world's premier female superhero makes any direct appearances in the world premiere that opened Tuesday at Marin Theatre Company, but aspects of her infuse the generations of feminists who inspired and were inspired by her in an idea-packed and brilliantly cartoon-enhanced play.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/performance/article/Wonder-Woman-would-approve-Lasso-of-Truth-5270112.php|title='Lasso of Truth' review: Wonder Woman and a 3-way|accessdate=June 25, 2014|work=SFGate|date=March 1, 2014|first=Robert |last=Hurwitt}}</ref>\n*''Behind the Eye'' from ''City Beat Cincinnati'': According to Carson Kreitzer's new script, Behind the Eye, premiering at the Cincinnati Playhouse, Lee Miller 'reflects light so well it seems that she herself is the source.' Miller, you see, is a forgotten but real historical figure, a photographer's model in Vogue in the 1920s, a photographer herself in the 1930s and a fearless photojournalist across Europe during World War II. By any standards she was promiscuous and willful, a free spirit for whom happiness was just beyond her grasp. She is the fascinating focal point for Kreitzer's compelling new play [...], perhaps the best piece of theater at the Playhouse this season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://citybeat.com/cincinnati/article-23063-behind-the-eye-(review).html|title=Behind the Eye (Review)|accessdate=June 25, 2014|first=Rick|last=Pender|date=April 11, 2011|work=CityBeat|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140707155448/http://citybeat.com/cincinnati/article-23063-behind-the-eye-(review).html|archive-date=July 7, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*''1:23'' from Atlanta's ''Creative Loafing'': Playwright Carson Kreitzer's drama draws on elements of police procedurals like Law & Order in its investigation of the crimes of Susan Smith and two other notorious mothers who killed their children. In 1:23, we know whodunit, so the more pressing question becomes, 'Why did they do it?' Kreitzer's script finds clues in official records, urban legends and Latin-American folklore, placing the killings in complex, almost baffling cultural and psychological contexts. [...] Few themes prove as big or challenging as the ones raised in 1:23. If anything, the play's ambition nearly overleaps itself in its attempt to address too many ideas in too limited a time. 1:23 serves as a harrowing thematic symphony that can be overly pretentious and opaque, yet also builds to some genuine revelations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://clatl.com/atlanta/synchronicitys-123-medea-blitz/Content?oid=1279465|title=Synchronicity's 1:23 Medea blitz |accessdate=June 25, 2014|publisher=Creative Loafing Atlanta|date=April 20, 2009|first=Curt |last=Holman}}</ref>\n*''Valerie Shoots Andy'' from ''[[The New York Times]]'': Ms. Kreitzer offers an assessment of how Solanas's play (''Up Your Ass'') and a diatribe she wrote shortly before the shooting called the SCUM manifesto evolved into gunshots. It is a bleak but fascinating piece that plays with Warhol's notions of repetition, returning to the shooting and its immediate aftermath again and again as it fleshes out the portrait of Solanas, who died in 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/03/01/theater/theater-review-writer-one-day-would-be-killer-next-reliving-warhol-shooting.html|title=Theater Review \u2014 A Writer One Day, a Would-Be Killer the Next: Reliving the Warhol Shooting|accessdate=June 25, 2014|work=[[The New York Times]]|date= March 1, 2001|first=Neil |last=Genzlinger}}</ref>\n\n== In Development ==\n\n* ''Runway 69'' a new musical, \"a provocative story of one of the raunchiest strip clubs in mid-1990\u2019s Times Square, and the lives of the men and women who work there.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.erinkamler.net/musicals/runway-69/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140625155856/http://www.erinkamler.net/musicals/runway-69/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 25, 2014 |title=Runway 69 |accessdate=June 25, 2014 |publisher=Erin Kamler }}</ref> Workshopped at the 2013 The Ground Floor<ref>{{cite web|url=http://berkeleyrep.org/groundfloor/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505020903/http://berkeleyrep.org/groundfloor/|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 May 2014|title=The Ground Floor at Berkeley Rep|date=5 May 2014}}</ref> summer residency lab at [[Berkeley Rep]]. Book and lyrics by Krietzer; Music, Lyrics, and original concept by Erin Kamler.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.erinkamler.net/bio/|title=Bio|publisher=}}</ref>\n* ''Lempicka'' a new musical inspired by \"the tempestuous life of [[Art Deco]] artist [[Tamara de Lempicka]].\" Commissioned by [[Yale Rep]] and New Dramatists. Book and lyrics by Krietzer; music by composer Matt Gould.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newdramatists.org/events/2012-10-29/full-stage-usa-carson-kreitzer|title=Full Stage USA: Carson Kreitzer|accessdate=June 25, 2014|publisher=New Dramatists}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.carsonkreitzer.com}}\n* [http://newdramatists.org/carson-kreitzer Carson Kreitzer at New Dramatists]\n* [http://www.playscripts.com/author.php3?authorid=276 Carson Kreitzer at Playscripts, Inc.]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130806174824/http://www.workhauscollective.org/Site/Now.html Workhaus Collective]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140607021458/http://www.parksquaretheatre.org/www/pst-showpage-eye.php Carson Kreitzer at Doollee.com]\n* [http://americantheatrewing.org/recipients/carson-kreitzer/ Carson Kreitzer's Jonathan Larson Grant performance]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kreitzer, Carson}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Michener Center for Writers alumni]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carson_Kreitzer"}
